{"timestamp": "2025-12-02 14:06:42.165775", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting diagnosis report — network snapshot analysis\n\nScope and method\n- Source data: full reachability (ICMP) matrix collected across the lab.\n- Focus: detect anomalies, localize faulty devices/segments, identify likely root cause(s).\n- Note: I did not apply any fixes — this is an observation / diagnosis-only report.\n\nHigh-level summary\n- The server farm and load balancer (10.200.0.0/24 and 10.200.0.7) are largely reachable and show healthy intra‑server connectivity. The load balancer reaches its backend web nodes (20.200.0.x) properly.\n- However, a subset of host subnets/hosts show significant reachability problems: (a) many ping attempts are “unknown” (no result) from some sources, and (b) several hosts/segments show high, non-trivial packet loss (25–75%) to infrastructure (DHCP, DNS, servers) and other hosts.\n- The pattern indicates a partial network partition or intermittent packet loss affecting a particular distribution/access region rather than a global core or server-farm outage.\n\nDetailed findings / evidence\n\n1) Server-farm and load-balancer (healthy)\n- load_balancer -> backend_web_0/1/2: pings successful, 0% loss, RTTs ~1 ms (internal).\n- Backend servers and web servers (10.200.0.x) show full interconnectivity and low RTTs among themselves and to the load balancer and DHCP server.\n- dhcp_server and dns_server respond to pings from many hosts with low RTTs.\n\n2) Hosts / segments with high packet loss\n- Example: host_2_2_1_2 (10.2.2.x) reported 25% packet loss to:\n  - web_server_1 (10.200.0.4) — 25% loss\n  - web_server_2 (10.200.0.5) — 25% loss\n  - dns_server (10.200.0.2) — 25% loss\n  These losses are consistent across multiple destination types (server and DNS), which points to a path issue rather than a single destination fault.\n\n- Example: host_2_2_1_1 shows multiple severe degradations:\n  - 50% loss to several hosts (including dhcp_server and load_balancer in some entries),\n  - 75% loss to host_1_1_2_2 in at least one test,\n  - Large swathes of “unknown”/null results for other destinations.\n  This indicates either an intermittent link/drop condition or an upstream device intermittently dropping traffic for that host/segment.\n\n3) Many “unknown” / null reachability entries\n- Numerous source hosts return \"unknown\" for a wide set of destinations (no ping results recorded). This is not limited to backend 20.200.x addresses (which are expected to be inaccessible from user subnets by design) — it also affects core infrastructure from those sources.\n- Example groups with extensive unknowns: host_2_2_2_2, host_2_1_2_1, several host_1_2_* and host_1_1_* entries. This pattern is consistent with a measurement failure or a segment that is isolated (no IP forwarding/route or link down).\n\n4) Pattern of affected addresses (localization clues)\n- The problematic sources cluster around the “2_x_x” naming (several 10.2.* hosts show loss or unknowns), and some inter-area traffic between \"2.*\" hosts and \"1.*\" hosts experiences very high loss.\n- Access/distribution devices in the topology associated with the affected subnets are:\n  - router_dist_2_1 (distribution router for many 10.2.* subnets)\n  - switch_access_2_1_1 (access switch feeding hosts in that dist segment)\n  The topology shows switch_access_2_1_1 connected to router_dist_2_1, and hosts behind that switch match the naming of the affected hosts.\n\n5) Deliberately unreachable addresses behave as expected\n- Backend web addresses in 20.200.0.x are often “unknown” from end-hosts — that is consistent with the design note that backends are not directly reachable by hosts (access should be via the load balancer).\n\nProbable localization (faulty device / segment)\n- The problem is localized to one distribution/access region:\n  - Primary suspect: router_dist_2_1 and/or its downstream access switch switch_access_2_1_1 (the segment serving the 10.2.* host subnets).\n- Evidence:\n  - Multiple hosts in the 10.2.* area show consistent packet loss (25–75%) to core services (DHCP, DNS, load balancer) and to other subnets.\n  - Some hosts in that general area have many “unknowns” (isolation).\n  - Server-farm side (10.200.0.0/24) and core-to-core links appear healthy, so the fault sits between the affected hosts and the core/server access, most likely at the dist/access layer.\n\nLikely root cause(s)\n- Strong candidates (based on observed symptoms):\n  1) Intermittent link or interface failure at router_dist_2_1 (or its link to the core) — causing packet drops and intermittent reachability for hosts in that distribution area.\n     - Symptoms matching: partial packet loss percentages (25–75%), asymmetrical reachability (some pings succeed, others drop).\n  2) Faulty or partially down access switch (switch_access_2_1_1) or an issue on the access link(s) between the switch and the distribution router — causing host isolation (many “unknown” results) for some hosts.\n  3) Misconfigured ACL / ICMP rate limiting or control-plane policing on the distribution router or access switch impacting ICMP/traffic from these host ranges — explains fractional packet loss (25%/50% patterns) if some ICMP replies get dropped or rate-limited.\n  4) OSPF/routing misconfiguration for those prefixes (less likely given that some pings succeed and server-network advertisements appear present) — this would cause entirely missing connectivity rather than intermittent loss, so it's considered a secondary possibility if further tests show missing routes.\n\nAdditional observations relevant to root cause:\n- The exact fractional loss rates (25%, 50%, 75%) suggest intermittent behavior (possible interface flaps, packet policers, or scheduled drops) rather than a steady congestion effect.\n- The server farm and load balancer are functional and reachable from other areas, and the load balancer can reach backend web nodes — so core and server-side routing/OSP